The official ball for the 2019 football Africa Cup of Nations (CAN) the Umbro Neo Pro is pictured during a press conference by Confederation of African Football (CAF) President on June 20, 2019 at the Cairo International Stadium in the Egyptian capital. JOHANNESBURG – Africa’s biggest nations will go toe to toe in the 32nd edition of the Africa Cup of Nations (Afcon) as the tournament kicks off on Friday. eNCA.com takes a look at the most influential players set to participate in the prestigious tournament. Percy Tau (Union SG, on-loan Brighton & Hove Albion) South Africa's Percy Tau is tackled by Seychelles' Nigel Nigel during the African Cup of Nations qualifier football match between South Africa and The Seychelles. Blessed with blistering pace and an eye for goal the South African international scored 12 goals in 35 appearances across all competitions for Belgian Second Division side Union SG in the 2018/19 season. Tau made his international debut for Bafana Bafana in 2015. Mohamed Salah (Liverpool) Egypt's forward Mohamed Salah (L) fights for the ball with Saudi Arabia's defender Motaz Hawsawi during the Russia 2018 World Cup Group A football match between Saudi Arabia and Egypt at the Volgograd Arena. Known for his dribbling, finishing and speed the Egyptian international is arguably the biggest star ahead of this year’s tournament. The Liverpool goal poacher hit 27 goals in 52 appearances across all competitions in the 2018/19 season. Salah made his international debut for The Pharaohs in 2011 bagging 39 goals in 64 caps to date. Wilfred Zaha (Crystal Palace) Ivory Coast's forward Wilfred Zaha (L) advances with the ball past Democratic Republic of the Congo's forward Firmin Ndombe Mubele during the 2017 Africa Cup of Nations group C football match between Ivory Coast and DR Congo. The two-footed forward is a tricky customer with the ball at his feet as the Ivorian international scored 10 goals in 36 appearances for Crystal Palace in the 2019/20 season. Zaha switched his all international allegiance from England to the Ivory Coast in 2016 and made his debut for The Elephants in 2017. He’s scored 2 goals in 11 internationals. Hakim Ziyech (Ajax Amsterdam) Morocco's midfielder Hakim Ziyech (R) is marked by Cameroon's defender Jerome Onguene during the Africa Cup of Nations qualifier football match between Morocco and Cameroon. Gifted with great technical ability and an educated left foot. The Morrocco international amassed 21 goals in 49 appearances in the 2019/20 season. Ziyech made his international debut in 2015 and has managed to earn 25 caps accompanied by his 14 goals for the Atlas Lions. Nicolas Pepe (Lille) Ivory Coast's Nicolas Pepe (L) vies for the ball with Rwanda's Emmaunel Imanishimwe (R) during the 2019 African Cup of Nations Group H qualification football match between Ivory Coast and Rwanda. New boy on the block Nicolas Pepe experienced a breakthrough season in 2019/20 following his 23 goals in 41 appearances for Lille. The forward made his international debut for the Ivory Coast in 2016 scoring 4 goals in 11 appearances.